{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637444"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:43:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:43:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17663"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17663","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17663"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10377"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78232"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10377"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17663"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63641"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"8485"},{"type":"tags","id":"10538"},{"type":"tags","id":"10539"},{"type":"tags","id":"10542"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24265"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24301"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78232","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78232"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe phosphate buffer system plays a crucial role in maintaining acid-base balance, particularly in the renal tubules.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the phosphate buffer system in human physiology?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Exists primarily as H3PO4 in physiological conditions","Requires carbonic anhydrase for function","Acts primarily in the blood plasma","Functions optimally at blood pH of 7.4","Has maximum buffering capacity at pH 6.8"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe phosphate buffer system \u003Cstrong\u003Ehas maximum buffering capacity at pH 6.8\u003C/strong\u003E, which corresponds to its pKa. This makes it particularly effective in the proximal renal tubules where pH varies around this range.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExists primarily as H3PO4 in physiological conditions\u003C/strong\u003E - At physiological pH (7.4), phosphate exists predominantly as HPO42-.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequires carbonic anhydrase for function\u003C/strong\u003E - Unlike the bicarbonate buffer system, the phosphate buffer system functions independently of enzymatic catalysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActs primarily in the blood plasma\u003C/strong\u003E - While phosphate is present in blood, its buffering action is most significant in the renal tubules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFunctions optimally at blood pH of 7.4\u003C/strong\u003E - This pH is too far from the pKa of phosphate (6.8) to provide effective buffering capacity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe phosphate buffer system works by the reversible reaction: HPO42- + H+ \u21cc H2PO4-. This allows it to accept or donate hydrogen ions to help maintain acid-base balance, particularly in the urine where its concentration is higher than in blood. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The phosphate buffer system is most important in the renal tubules with optimal buffering capacity at urinary pH.","In the phosphate buffer system, phosphate exists primarily as HPO42- at a pH of 7.4, and H2PO4- at a pH of 6.8.","The phosphate buffer system helps maintain acid-base balance by accepting or donating hydrogen ions, which can then be absorbed or excreted in the renal tubule."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63641"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17663"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63641"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T22:10:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T22:10:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10377"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78232"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"ta